        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging requirements:
We plan to use the C34-7 configuration of the array to image the
H26alpha recombination line (353.623 GHz; band 7) towards the
hypercompact HII region G24.78+0.08 A1, achieving an angular
resolution of 0.12 arcsec. Note that the source will be only
barely resolved (size around 0.15 arcsec), so that we have no
problem with structures extending beyond the maximum angular scale
that can be imaged (around 2.5 arcsec).

Correlator setup:
We will cover the H26alpha line with a 937.5 MHz band unit, with
double polarization and an spectral resolution of 1.9 MHz. We plan
to smooth the H26alpha spectrum to 4 km/s, which will still suffice
to resolve the broad profile (see Fig.2) and will greatly improve
the S/N. The correlator setup is chosen in such a way to cover
other potentially interesting (hot core) tracers such as the
13CH3CN(19-18), C33S(7-6), CH3CCH(20-19), CN(3-2) and HCN(4-3)
transitions. From the line-free channels we will also obtain a
measurement of the continuum emission. From Beltran et al (2007)
we extrapolate a free-free, optically thin flux of 70 mJy at
354 GHz for the HII region and thus plan to use this compact
emission for self-calibrating our data.

Requested sensitivity:
As shown in Fig.2, the expected line strength is at least 12 K;
however, for our purposes it is not sufficient to detect the line,
but we want to reveal the dip at the line center. The difference
between the peaks and the dip is around 6 K and we want to attain
a S/N=10, which implies a 1sigma RMS of 0.6 K. According to the OT
time estimator, this requires 1.57 hours on-source and a total time
of 3.63 hours.

Time constraints: None

User defined calibrations: None</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
