    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to image the H26alpha recombination line in band 7 with the goal to establish the kinematics of the ionised gas in the hypercompact HII region G24.78+0.08A1. High-angular resolution observations of the free-free continuum emission have revealed that this HII region (which lies at the center of a rotating and infalling hot molecular core) has a shell-like morphology, with several water maser spots distributed along the border. The 3D velocity field traced by the masers can be interpreted either as expansion with a dynamical litetime of only 50 years, or as drift of the HII region with respect to the surrounding molecular core. A measurement of the profile of the H26alpha line towards the center of the HII region will suffice to discriminate between these two possible scenarios. In fact, if the ionised gas lies in an expanding shell, our model predicts that the line should be double peaked. Should expansion be confirmed, our observations will lend strong support to models predicting initial confinment of the HII region. Vice versa, a non-expanding HII region would lead to an intriguing case of a massive star moving through the associated clump at extremely high velocities.</prp:abstract>
